"in nature, initially by Fritz Zwicky, with widespread cataloguing
later by individuals such as George O. Abell in the early-to-mid
20th century (e.g. Zwicky 1937; Abell 1958) to a more extensive
scale by modern spectroscopic galaxy surveys (e.g. 2dFGRS, Col-
less et al. 2001). Our comprehension of how matter - baryonic (pro-
tons, neutrons, electrons) and dark - collapses to form these struc-
tures (and the rate at which this happens) is partially governed by
our understanding of cosmology (e.g. BAHAMAS, McCarthy et al.
2018)."
