identifiers in order to differentiate between different ‘layers’ of the
masks - namely artifacts/saturated stars vs. objects. From these, we
generate our mask layers via 3 stages:"
"(i) Bad Pixel Masking: we begin by first identifying the ‘bad
pixel’ regions thresholded out by the HSC pipeline. These regions
are then masked out, and constitute the first mask layer. These in-
clude: regions which have been incorrectly weighted by the weight
maps, saturated pixels and some of the artifacts generated by bright
stars."
"(ii) Star Masking: next, we run SExtractor across all of the im-
ages. We set a detection threshold for our objects at 10σ; with other
parameters (such as saturation level, etc.) set to roughly the same
values as those used during our running of SIGMA. We allow SEx-
tractor to approximate a rough background level using a large mesh
size to account for any extended bright sources (128 pixels). The
purpose of this step is primarily to identify brighter, more compact
objects within the frame, for which we do not require absolutely
accurate photometry."
